And at Brompton,
we've had-- well, I

00:32:59.080 --> 00:33:02.970
used to work for ICI and
DuPont and these big companies,

00:33:02.970 --> 00:33:06.470
and I was involved in
project management.

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:08.850
So we did project
management, and we used

00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:11.000
to sort of do these projects.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.770
And we had to have a
three-year payback.

00:33:13.770 --> 00:33:14.560
So guess what?

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:16.730
We wrote this great
business plan.

00:33:16.730 --> 00:33:19.289
We had to have a three-year
payback, a three-year payback,

00:33:19.289 --> 00:33:20.330
two and 1/2 year payback.

00:33:20.330 --> 00:33:21.920
Then we had a little piece of
paper that had to go around,

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:23.400
and everyone had to sign it.

00:33:23.400 --> 00:33:25.737
And that's basically ass
covering, that piece of paper.

00:33:25.737 --> 00:33:27.570
And as long as enough
people have signed it,

00:33:27.570 --> 00:33:29.010
everyone saw that somebody
else has signed it,

00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:31.020
and then it's all fine, because
no one's taking responsibility,

00:33:31.020 --> 00:33:31.730
because they've all signed it.

00:33:31.730 --> 00:33:32.290
So it's fine.

00:33:32.290 --> 00:33:33.630
And it says less than
three-year payback.

00:33:33.630 --> 00:33:34.480
So that's all fine.

00:33:34.480 --> 00:33:37.250
It's all going to be great.

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:39.610
But the problem is, if
you have enough experience

00:33:39.610 --> 00:33:42.444
of these types of projects,
they never add up,

00:33:42.444 --> 00:33:43.860
because they're
based on something

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:48.390
called an assumption that's
deep in the guts of a project.

00:33:48.390 --> 00:33:52.530
And the assumption is basically
just a sort of educated guess,

00:33:52.530 --> 00:33:55.850
and it spins out
certain effects.

00:33:55.850 --> 00:33:57.800
And, of course, I
loved my projects,

00:33:57.800 --> 00:33:59.560
and I wasn't going to have
somebody else get the money

00:33:59.560 --> 00:34:01.490
that I wanted for my project so
of course my assumptions were

00:34:01.490 --> 00:34:03.240
maybe a little bit on
the optimistic side.

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:04.620
That's the nature of the beast.

00:34:04.620 --> 00:34:06.980
So we have a part of
our business, which

00:34:06.980 --> 00:34:10.739
is where we do far less
research and development,

00:34:10.739 --> 00:34:16.230
far less endless
justification for investment,

00:34:16.230 --> 00:34:19.670
and we look at the downside.

00:34:19.670 --> 00:34:24.920
So in your business, rather
than always assuming the upside,

00:34:24.920 --> 00:34:28.322
give yourself more
flexibility, less bureaucracy,

00:34:28.322 --> 00:34:30.530
and say to yourself at the
beginning of the year-- so

00:34:30.530 --> 00:34:32.364
in our case, we don't
have it at the moment,

00:34:32.364 --> 00:34:34.654
because we're so full of
projects we've got to deliver,

00:34:34.654 --> 00:34:35.710
there is no fuck-it fund.

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:38.580
But for a long time,
we did have it.

00:34:38.580 --> 00:34:42.620
And basically, we had a fund
that's basically fuck it.

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:43.690
It's the fuck-it fund.

00:34:43.690 --> 00:34:49.719
Started at 5 grand, and
we had a 5-grand pot,

00:34:49.719 --> 00:34:53.179
and we decided to just give
it a go, try something.

00:34:53.179 --> 00:34:55.590
And that justification
was not the upside.

00:34:55.590 --> 00:34:57.630
That justification
is the downside.

00:34:57.630 --> 00:35:00.530
So in a project, if
everything goes wrong,

00:35:00.530 --> 00:35:01.630
what are you in for?

00:35:01.630 --> 00:35:06.770
That is a much more exact
amount in terms of reputation,

00:35:06.770 --> 00:35:07.950
in terms of cost.

00:35:07.950 --> 00:35:09.160
You can measure that.

00:35:09.160 --> 00:35:11.800
And if you can measure that and
you know you can afford that,

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:13.230
then just do it.

00:35:13.230 --> 00:35:15.420
Don't go through endless
analysis and tons

00:35:15.420 --> 00:35:16.380
of market research.

00:35:16.380 --> 00:35:17.800
It costs you a fortune.

00:35:17.800 --> 00:35:19.070
Give it a try and find out.

00:35:19.070 --> 00:35:22.120
Now, if you try it, and
it's a complete disaster,

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:24.480
you stick a sign up and say
do not go down this alley,

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:25.604
because it does not work.

00:35:25.604 --> 00:35:27.020
So you've got
something out of it.

00:35:27.020 --> 00:35:29.360
If you try it, and you think,
hey, that was pretty cool.

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:30.610
Maybe there's more to do here.

00:35:30.610 --> 00:35:35.090
Then you do more research,
and you justify your research,

00:35:35.090 --> 00:35:37.660
and you understand and you
go after that business.

00:35:37.660 --> 00:35:42.160
The business, the
electric bike, the E-bike.

00:35:42.160 --> 00:35:43.290
Our first store.

00:35:43.290 --> 00:35:47.840
We're all sodded,
bugger it, you know.

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:48.560
Who cares?

00:35:48.560 --> 00:35:51.130
Just do it.

00:35:51.130 --> 00:35:53.680
But do it with a
controlled downside.

00:35:53.680 --> 00:35:56.542
