AUDIENCE: Do you feel
you'll get enough support

00:43:43.240 --> 00:43:46.067
from the government to
continue production in the UK?

00:43:46.067 --> 00:43:47.900
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: I
think any business that

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:51.280
replies on any government
for their well-being

00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:54.280
needs to have their heads
inspected, because you

00:43:54.280 --> 00:43:56.840
can't rely on the
government for anything.

00:43:56.840 --> 00:43:59.060
The fact is governments
come and go.

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:01.360
Like we were saying earlier,
they mean their best.

00:44:01.360 --> 00:44:03.760
If there are little bits
that help us along our way,

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:06.404
I'll scoop them up,
and they've been great.

00:44:06.404 --> 00:44:08.320
What we got from the
Technology Strategy Board

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:11.790
was awesome, because
it-- my board were always

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:13.964
a bit worried.

00:44:13.964 --> 00:44:15.880
And the fact that somebody
from the government

00:44:15.880 --> 00:44:17.921
had said it's a good idea
and given us 200 grand,

00:44:17.921 --> 00:44:21.720
they're like, oh well, we can't
say no to that then, can we?

00:44:21.720 --> 00:44:24.520
And R&amp;D tax credits, thank you
very much, we'll have those.

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:25.900
They genuinely
make a difference.

00:44:25.900 --> 00:44:27.910
Patent box, that genuinely
makes a difference.

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:31.120
But if you took everything
away, if the business can't

00:44:31.120 --> 00:44:35.560
stand on its own two
feet in its own world,

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:37.497
then you are in trouble.

00:44:37.497 --> 00:44:39.580
Personally, I'd feel very
uncomfortable with that.

00:44:39.580 --> 00:44:41.620
So there's far more the
government could do.

00:44:41.620 --> 00:44:43.750
The most important thing
the government could do

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:46.090
is stop spending
tens of billions

00:44:46.090 --> 00:44:48.400
of pounds on
digging more tunnels

00:44:48.400 --> 00:44:50.920
and putting in infrastructure
before they spent

00:44:50.920 --> 00:44:53.670
2 billion pounds making
cycle lanes across cities,

00:44:53.670 --> 00:44:55.850
because that is so
much better value.

00:44:55.850 --> 00:44:58.240
And it would make our
cities a better place.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:44:59.610
But that's coming.

00:44:59.610 --> 00:45:01.440
It's just taking
rather a long time.

00:45:01.440 --> 00:45:04.085
AUDIENCE: So I've not
heard of the rental boxes.

00:45:04.085 --> 00:45:05.085
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: Yeah.

00:45:05.085 --> 00:45:06.960
AUDIENCE: I'm totally
going to try that now.

00:45:06.960 --> 00:45:10.490
But what is preventing
the larger rollout?

00:45:10.490 --> 00:45:12.870
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: Cash.

00:45:12.870 --> 00:45:15.400
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:17.300
It costs you.

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:19.520
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: Well,
it costs somebody else.

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:23.224
So we sell the dock
and we sell the bikes.

00:45:23.224 --> 00:45:24.640
So we have to sell
it to somebody.

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:27.790
We are not funding it, but
we sell it to somebody,

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:29.910
they put it in place, and
then they get bike hire,

00:45:29.910 --> 00:45:31.230
and it costs them nothing.

00:45:31.230 --> 00:45:33.240
At the moment, the
Boris scheme is about 25

00:45:33.240 --> 00:45:36.440
grand a bike to put on
the streets of London.

00:45:36.440 --> 00:45:39.670
And then it's costing
GLA 12 million a year.

00:45:39.670 --> 00:45:41.480
And the outer boroughs
that are funding it

00:45:41.480 --> 00:45:42.870
are not getting any bike hire.

00:45:42.870 --> 00:45:44.620
And you couldn't put
that bike hire scheme

00:45:44.620 --> 00:45:47.050
into greater London, because it
would make even bigger losses,

00:45:47.050 --> 00:45:48.258
and it would cost more money.

00:45:48.258 --> 00:45:49.140
So it's not viable.

00:45:49.140 --> 00:45:51.140
It's fine for capital
wealthy cities,

00:45:51.140 --> 00:45:53.790
but it's not viable for
Leeds, for Sheffield,

00:45:53.790 --> 00:45:55.100
for other cities.

00:45:55.100 --> 00:45:58.360
So we've created something
and also if you go back,

00:45:58.360 --> 00:46:01.550
start to get quite
cool, but this scheme

00:46:01.550 --> 00:46:04.850
has retrofitability
of electric bikes,

00:46:04.850 --> 00:46:07.700
because everybody else is trying
to charge the electric bike

00:46:07.700 --> 00:46:08.980
in the docking station.

00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:11.322
And all urban cycling
is going to go electric,

00:46:11.322 --> 00:46:13.030
but that's a big
mistake, because then it

00:46:13.030 --> 00:46:16.634
makes the docking station--
you have to put more power in.

00:46:16.634 --> 00:46:17.550
This is solar powered.

00:46:17.550 --> 00:46:20.120
You just drop it on the street,
half an hour, it's live.

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:22.536
Theirs, you have to dig up the
street, planning commission

00:46:22.536 --> 00:46:26.440
lawyers, ripoff, and with
electric bike it's even worse.

00:46:26.440 --> 00:46:30.725
But in ours, the electric
drive, the power pack

00:46:30.725 --> 00:46:31.870
is in your luggage.

00:46:31.870 --> 00:46:34.805
So if you're an electric user,
you would get sent luggage.

00:46:34.805 --> 00:46:36.180
And then all that
would happen is

00:46:36.180 --> 00:46:37.250
a door would open
with the solar power,

00:46:37.250 --> 00:46:38.320
and then you just
click your power on,

00:46:38.320 --> 00:46:39.778
and you'd be in
control your power.

00:46:39.778 --> 00:46:41.510
So there's all
sorts of cool stuff.

00:46:41.510 --> 00:46:43.942
But I suppose we're
not VC backed,

00:46:43.942 --> 00:46:45.900
we're a privately owned
company, and we've only

00:46:45.900 --> 00:46:46.650
got so much money.

00:46:46.650 --> 00:46:49.960
And probably we're
taking on too much.

00:46:49.960 --> 00:46:53.310
At the moment, it's costing
us about 30 grand a month,

00:46:53.310 --> 00:46:53.870
that project.

00:46:53.870 --> 00:46:56.440
We've invested probably
[INAUDIBLE] about a million

00:46:56.440 --> 00:46:59.920
quid in that project
so far funding it.

00:46:59.920 --> 00:47:03.480
And it's so awesome,
but it's flipping hard,

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:06.700
and also sticking out across
the country is quite difficult.

00:47:06.700 --> 00:47:07.280
Anyone else?

00:47:07.280 --> 00:47:08.155
SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:08.155 --> 00:47:09.970
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:47:09.970 --> 00:47:12.040
I wonder what you think
of other companies that

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:14.390
are sort of disrupting
travel a little bit,

00:47:14.390 --> 00:47:16.092
in particular Tesla--

00:47:16.092 --> 00:47:17.050
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: Yes.

00:47:17.050 --> 00:47:18.549
AUDIENCE: --the
electric car people.

00:47:18.549 --> 00:47:20.852
They seem similar, albeit
much newer than you.

00:47:20.852 --> 00:47:22.810
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: He's
getting a bit more help

00:47:22.810 --> 00:47:25.330
from the government than I am.

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:31.492
I just think it's
interesting times.

00:47:31.492 --> 00:47:33.450
The average age of the
people getting a driving

00:47:33.450 --> 00:47:36.810
license in the US has
moved from 17.4 to 19.2

00:47:36.810 --> 00:47:37.840
in the last 10 years.

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:41.500
So people are not needing to
have that driving license.

00:47:41.500 --> 00:47:43.950
So things are shifting.

00:47:43.950 --> 00:47:49.740
The question is, can we remain
private and have enough revenue

00:47:49.740 --> 00:47:53.290
to innovate at the speed
that we need to to retain

00:47:53.290 --> 00:47:55.480
a viable competitive product?

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:56.889
And that's debatable.

00:47:56.889 --> 00:47:58.930
The next three or four
years will be interesting.

00:47:58.930 --> 00:48:01.100
The interesting thing
about the car industry

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:05.604
is they keep just trying
to make more cars.

00:48:05.604 --> 00:48:07.020
They don't sort
of realize they're

00:48:07.020 --> 00:48:09.360
in the transport industry,
and they pretend they are.

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:10.210
They talk about mobility.

00:48:10.210 --> 00:48:12.060
They keep making cars,
and they're big boxes,

00:48:12.060 --> 00:48:14.393
and they're quite heavy, and
they're not that efficient.

00:48:14.393 --> 00:48:17.360
This thing, our electric
bike weighs 11, 12 kilos,

00:48:17.360 --> 00:48:18.710
and it carries me.

00:48:18.710 --> 00:48:22.010
A car that's electric
weighs 1,000 kilos.

00:48:22.010 --> 00:48:23.000
It's flipping nuts.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:23.750
It's inefficient.

00:48:23.750 --> 00:48:25.083
You're carrying all that weight.

00:48:25.083 --> 00:48:27.522
So it's going to be interesting.

00:48:27.522 --> 00:48:28.730
And I don't know the outcome.

00:48:28.730 --> 00:48:29.890
AUDIENCE: But I guess they're
interesting because they're

00:48:29.890 --> 00:48:31.730
cars but not so much
like other ones.

00:48:31.730 --> 00:48:32.230
And your--

00:48:32.230 --> 00:48:32.710
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS: The
interesting thing--

00:48:32.710 --> 00:48:33.850
AUDIENCE: And yours are
bikes but they're not

00:48:33.850 --> 00:48:34.870
so much like other one.

00:48:34.870 --> 00:48:36.536
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS:
The thing about Tesla

00:48:36.536 --> 00:48:40.490
is, the barrier to entry for
developing an electric engine

00:48:40.490 --> 00:48:42.710
is far less than an
internal combustion engine.

00:48:42.710 --> 00:48:45.020
So, again, the point is,
the internal combustion

00:48:45.020 --> 00:48:47.040
engine required
massive industry,

00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:48.870
massive collaboration.

00:48:48.870 --> 00:48:51.000
Electric engines are
pretty easy to make.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.690
So that is going to open up
that industry quite a bit.

00:48:53.690 --> 00:48:57.670
But if you look at his accounts,
there's been-- basically,

00:48:57.670 --> 00:49:00.500
the US government
has given up on GM

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:03.067
and just shifted their enormous
great subsidies into Tesla,

00:49:03.067 --> 00:49:03.650
but it's good.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:04.760
At least he's doing
some innovative stuff.

00:49:04.760 --> 00:49:05.551
I think it's great.

00:49:05.551 --> 00:49:10.560
And the one I really like
is his vacuum rail thing,

00:49:10.560 --> 00:49:11.930
because that's flipping cool.

00:49:11.930 --> 00:49:15.317
If you can stick a train down a
vacuum, that would be awesome.

00:49:15.317 --> 00:49:17.650
AUDIENCE: And you could
probably carry a Brompton on it.

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:18.540
WILL BUTLER-ADAMS:
Yeah, of course.

00:49:18.540 --> 00:49:19.248
And that's there.

00:49:19.248 --> 00:49:20.215
End-to-end end journey.

00:49:20.215 --> 00:49:21.705
SPEAKER: With that,
we'll leave it there.

00:49:21.705 --> 00:49:22.250
Please join me in a
massive round of applause

00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:23.550
for Will Butler-Adams.

00:49:23.550 --> 00:49:25.100
[APPLAUSE]

